      content: "Penile erection is a complex neurovascular event requiring coordinated parasympathetic activation, endothelial nitric oxide (NO) release, and cavernosal smooth muscle relaxation. Sexual stimulation activates parasympathetic nerves (S2-S4 via pelvic splanchnic nerves) releasing acetylcholine, which stimulates endothelial cells to produce NO via endothelial nitric oxide synthase (eNOS). NO diffuses into cavernosal smooth muscle cells and activates soluble guanylate cyclase (sGC), converting GTP to cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP). cGMP activates protein kinase G (PKG), which reduces intracellular calcium by promoting calcium reuptake into the sarcoplasmic reticulum and opening potassium channels, causing smooth muscle relaxation.\n\nRelaxation of trabecular smooth muscle allows sinusoidal spaces to fill with arterial blood via helicine arteries branching from the deep penile (cavernosal) arteries. Expanding sinusoids compress subtunical venules against the tunica albuginea, activating the veno-occlusive mechanism that traps blood and maintains rigidity. Detumescence occurs when sympathetic tone returns, phosphodiesterase type 5 (PDE5) degrades cGMP, and smooth muscle contracts.\n\nErectile dysfunction (ED) results from disruption at any point in this cascade. Vasculogenic causes (60-80% of organic ED) include endothelial dysfunction from atherosclerosis, hypertension, diabetes mellitus, dyslipidemia, and smoking. Neurogenic causes include spinal cord injury, multiple sclerosis, pelvic surgery (radical prostatectomy), and peripheral neuropathy. Hormonal causes include testosterone deficiency (hypogonadism). Psychogenic ED involves cortical inhibition of spinal erection centers. Medication-induced ED is common with antihypertensives (beta-blockers, thiazides), SSRIs, antiandrogens, and 5-alpha reductase inhibitors."
