      content: "Testosterone is the primary androgen produced by Leydig cells in the testes under the regulation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis. The hypothalamus secretes gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) in pulsatile fashion (every 90-120 minutes) into the hypophyseal portal system. GnRH binds receptors on anterior pituitary gonadotroph cells, stimulating release of luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH). LH acts on Leydig cells via LH/hCG receptors coupled to adenylate cyclase-cAMP-protein kinase A signaling, upregulating steroidogenic acute regulatory protein (StAR) which facilitates cholesterol transport into mitochondria for conversion to pregnenolone by CYP11A1 (side-chain cleavage enzyme). Pregnenolone is then converted through sequential enzymatic steps (3-beta-HSD, CYP17A1) to testosterone.\n\nTestosterone circulates 98% protein-bound: approximately 60% to sex hormone-binding globulin (SHBG) with high affinity, and 38% to albumin with low affinity. Only 2% circulates as free (unbound) testosterone, which is the biologically active fraction. Total testosterone measurement captures all fractions; free or bioavailable testosterone better reflects androgenic activity, especially when SHBG is altered (elevated by aging, liver disease, hyperthyroidism, anticonvulsants; decreased by obesity, diabetes, hypothyroidism, glucocorticoids).\n\nMale hypogonadism is classified as primary (hypergonadotropic - testicular failure with elevated LH/FSH), secondary (hypogonadotropic - hypothalamic/pituitary dysfunction with low/inappropriately normal LH/FSH), or combined. Primary causes include Klinefelter syndrome (47,XXY), orchitis, testicular trauma, chemotherapy, and radiation. Secondary causes include pituitary adenoma, hyperprolactinemia, hemochromatosis, opioid use, obesity (aromatase-mediated estrogen excess suppresses GnRH), and Kallmann syndrome."
