    cellular: {
      title: "The Endocannabinoid System: CB1, CB2 & Endogenous Ligands",
      content: "The endocannabinoid system (ECS) is a ubiquitous lipid-based neuromodulatory system involved in homeostatic regulation of pain, mood, appetite, immune function, and memory. It comprises three core components: endocannabinoid ligands, cannabinoid receptors, and metabolic enzymes.\n\nEndocannabinoid ligands are arachidonic acid derivatives synthesized on demand from membrane phospholipids (not stored in vesicles). Anandamide (AEA, arachidonoylethanolamide) is a partial agonist at CB1 and weak agonist at CB2, synthesized by N-acyl phosphatidylethanolamine phospholipase D (NAPE-PLD) and degraded by fatty acid amide hydrolase (FAAH). 2-Arachidonoylglycerol (2-AG) is a full agonist at both CB1 and CB2, synthesized by diacylglycerol lipase (DAGL) and degraded by monoacylglycerol lipase (MAGL). Retrograde signaling is the primary mode: postsynaptic neurons synthesize endocannabinoids that travel backward across the synapse to bind presynaptic CB1 receptors, inhibiting neurotransmitter release.\n\nCB1 receptors are G-protein coupled receptors (Gi/o) predominantly expressed in the central nervous system: cortex, hippocampus, basal ganglia, cerebellum, hypothalamus, and periaqueductal gray. CB1 activation inhibits adenylate cyclase (reducing cAMP), activates inwardly rectifying potassium channels (hyperpolarization), and inhibits voltage-gated calcium channels (reducing neurotransmitter release). CB1 mediates the psychoactive effects of THC, modulates pain perception, appetite, memory consolidation, and motor coordination.\n\nCB2 receptors are primarily expressed on immune cells (macrophages, B cells, T cells, microglia) and peripheral tissues (spleen, tonsils, bone). CB2 activation modulates cytokine release, immune cell migration, and inflammatory cascades. CB2 does not produce psychoactive effects. CB2 agonists are being investigated for anti-inflammatory and neuroprotective applications.\n\nPhytocannabinoids from Cannabis sativa include delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), a partial CB1 agonist responsible for psychoactive effects, and cannabidiol (CBD), which has minimal CB1/CB2 affinity but modulates serotonin 5-HT1A receptors, TRPV1 vanilloid receptors, and GPR55 orphan receptors. CBD also inhibits FAAH, indirectly increasing anandamide levels."
    },
    riskFactors: ["Cannabis use disorder (9% lifetime risk in users, higher with early onset)", "Adolescent brain exposure (impairs prefrontal cortex development)", "Co-administration with CNS depressants (synergistic sedation)", "Synthetic cannabinoid use (K2/Spice - high potency, unpredictable toxicity)", "Psychiatric vulnerability (psychosis risk with high-THC cannabis in genetically predisposed)", "Pregnancy (THC crosses placenta, enters breast milk)", "Cardiovascular risk (THC increases heart rate, CO levels with smoking)", "Chronic use: cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome", "Drug interactions via CYP3A4 and CYP2C19 inhibition by CBD", "Driving impairment (THC impairs reaction time and divided attention)"],
    diagnostics: ["Screen with urine drug screen for THC metabolites (THC-COOH detectable 3-30 days depending on use frequency)", "Order CBC if chronic use (assess for polycythemia from smoking)", "Order liver function tests if prescribing CBD (hepatotoxicity risk, especially with valproic acid)", "Order ECG if cardiovascular symptoms (THC-induced tachycardia)", "Screen for cannabis use disorder using DSM-5 criteria (tolerance, withdrawal, impaired control)", "Assess psychiatric history before recommending cannabinoid therapy", "Monitor for cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome (cyclic vomiting, compulsive hot bathing, abdominal pain)", "Review medication interactions before prescribing CBD products"],
    management: ["Prescribe nabilone (Cesamet) 1-2 mg PO BID for chemotherapy-induced nausea/vomiting refractory to conventional antiemetics", "Prescribe dronabinol (Marinol) 2.5-5 mg PO BID for AIDS-associated anorexia/weight loss or CINV", "Prescribe nabiximols (Sativex, not FDA-approved but approved in Canada) oromucosal spray for MS spasticity (2.7 mg THC + 2.5 mg CBD per spray)", "Prescribe CBD (Epidiolex) for Dravet syndrome and Lennox-Gastaut syndrome: start 2.5 mg/kg BID, titrate to 5-10 mg/kg BID", "Counsel patients that smoking cannabis is not a prescribed medical therapy - vaporization or oral routes reduce pulmonary harm", "Monitor LFTs at baseline, 1 month, 3 months, and 6 months on CBD (Epidiolex)", "Assess for CYP drug interactions: CBD inhibits CYP3A4 and CYP2C19 (increases levels of clobazam, warfarin, valproate)", "Refer for substance use treatment if cannabis use disorder identified"],
    nursingActions: ["Educate patients on difference between approved cannabinoid medications and unregulated cannabis products", "Counsel on delayed onset of oral cannabinoids (30-90 minutes) vs inhaled (minutes) to prevent overconsumption", "Monitor for CNS depression when cannabinoids are combined with opioids, benzodiazepines, or alcohol", "Assess for cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome in chronic users presenting with cyclic vomiting", "Educate on driving impairment - THC impairs psychomotor function for 3-4 hours after use", "Monitor psychiatric symptoms (anxiety, paranoia, psychosis) during cannabinoid therapy", "Counsel on safe storage away from children (edible products resemble candy)", "Document complete cannabinoid use history including route, frequency, and products used"],
