    pearls: ["Synthetic cannabinoids (K2/Spice) are full CB1 agonists (vs THC partial agonist), producing more intense and unpredictable effects including seizures, psychosis, rhabdomyolysis, and death", "CBD inhibits CYP2C19 and CYP3A4, causing clinically significant interactions with clobazam (increases N-desmethylclobazam 3-fold), warfarin, and valproate", "Cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome classically presents with cyclic vomiting, compulsive hot bathing for symptom relief, and abdominal pain in chronic cannabis users - only treatment is cannabis cessation", "THC is lipophilic and accumulates in adipose tissue - elimination half-life is 25-36 hours in occasional users but can exceed 10 days in chronic heavy users", "The NP scope regarding cannabis prescribing varies by jurisdiction - know your provincial/state regulations and document clinical rationale for cannabinoid prescriptions"],
    quiz: [
      { question: "A patient on CBD (Epidiolex) for Lennox-Gastaut syndrome also takes clobazam. Which monitoring parameter is most critical?", options: ["Renal function (creatinine and BUN)", "Hepatic transaminases (ALT, AST)", "Complete blood count with differential", "Thyroid function tests"], correct: 1, rationale: "CBD causes dose-dependent hepatotoxicity with elevated transaminases, particularly when combined with valproic acid or clobazam. CBD inhibits CYP2C19, increasing clobazam active metabolite levels 3-fold, compounding hepatotoxic risk. LFTs must be monitored at baseline, 1 month, 3 months, and 6 months. Dose reduction of clobazam may be necessary." },
      { question: "Which receptor primarily mediates the psychoactive effects of THC?", options: ["CB2 receptors on immune cells", "CB1 receptors in the central nervous system", "5-HT1A serotonin receptors", "TRPV1 vanilloid receptors"], correct: 1, rationale: "CB1 receptors in the CNS (cortex, hippocampus, basal ganglia, cerebellum) mediate THC's psychoactive effects including euphoria, altered perception, impaired memory, and motor incoordination. CB2 receptors are primarily on immune cells and do not produce psychoactive effects. CBD acts on 5-HT1A and TRPV1 but with minimal psychoactivity." },
      { question: "What distinguishes synthetic cannabinoids (K2/Spice) from plant-derived THC pharmacologically?", options: ["Synthetic cannabinoids are CB2-selective with no CNS effects", "Synthetic cannabinoids are full CB1 agonists vs THC which is a partial agonist", "Synthetic cannabinoids have shorter duration of action", "Synthetic cannabinoids are less potent than THC"], correct: 1, rationale: "Synthetic cannabinoids are typically full agonists at CB1 receptors, whereas THC is a partial agonist. Full agonism produces a more intense maximal response with no ceiling effect, explaining the higher incidence of severe toxicity: seizures, psychosis, rhabdomyolysis, acute kidney injury, and death. They are also structurally diverse and often more potent than THC, with unpredictable pharmacokinetics." }
    ]
