    diagnostics: ["Diagnose AD clinically using Hanifin and Rajka criteria (3+ major and 3+ minor criteria)", "Order serum total IgE (often elevated but not diagnostic)", "Order specific IgE or skin prick testing for suspected allergen triggers (food, aeroallergen)", "Order skin biopsy only if diagnosis uncertain (spongiotic dermatitis pattern)", "Assess disease severity using SCORAD (Scoring Atopic Dermatitis) or EASI (Eczema Area and Severity Index)", "Order CBC with differential (eosinophilia supports atopic diagnosis)", "Screen for secondary bacterial infection (S. aureus culture from weeping/crusted lesions)", "Assess for herpes simplex superinfection (eczema herpeticum - medical emergency)", "Order patch testing if allergic contact dermatitis suspected as comorbidity"],
    management: ["Prescribe emollients as foundation of therapy: apply immediately after bathing to damp skin, fragrance-free, ceramide-containing preferred (CeraVe, Vanicream)", "Prescribe topical corticosteroids: mild (hydrocortisone 1-2.5% for face/intertriginous areas), moderate (triamcinolone 0.1% for body), potent (betamethasone 0.05% for lichenified/thick plaques) - step-down approach", "Prescribe topical calcineurin inhibitors for steroid-sparing maintenance: tacrolimus 0.03-0.1% ointment or pimecrolimus 1% cream (no skin atrophy risk, safe for face and skin folds)", "Prescribe crisaborole 2% ointment (PDE4 inhibitor) for mild-moderate AD", "Prescribe dupilumab (Dupixent) 300 mg SC every 2 weeks for moderate-severe AD (monoclonal antibody targeting IL-4 receptor alpha, blocking IL-4 and IL-13 signaling)", "Prescribe narrowband UVB phototherapy for widespread moderate AD", "Prescribe oral JAK inhibitors (upadacitinib 15-30 mg daily, abrocitinib 100-200 mg daily) for moderate-severe AD refractory to dupilumab", "Manage secondary S. aureus infection with topical mupirocin or systemic antibiotics if widespread"],
