      { question: "A 28-year-old with moderate atopic dermatitis has persistent facial eczema. Hydrocortisone 1% provides minimal relief. What is the most appropriate next step?", options: ["Prescribe betamethasone 0.05% for the face", "Prescribe tacrolimus 0.1% ointment for facial application", "Start systemic prednisone 40 mg daily", "Refer for allergy testing before changing treatment"], correct: 1, rationale: "Tacrolimus 0.1% ointment is the preferred step-up for facial eczema that fails low-potency topical steroids. Unlike corticosteroids, calcineurin inhibitors do not cause skin atrophy, striae, or telangiectasia - critical for facial skin. Potent topical steroids (betamethasone) are contraindicated on the face due to atrophy risk. Systemic steroids are reserved for severe flares and cause rebound upon withdrawal." },
      { question: "Which genetic mutation is the strongest known risk factor for atopic dermatitis?", options: ["BRCA1 mutation", "Filaggrin (FLG) gene loss-of-function mutation", "HLA-B27", "CFTR mutation"], correct: 1, rationale: "Loss-of-function mutations in the filaggrin (FLG) gene are the strongest known genetic risk factor for atopic dermatitis. Filaggrin is essential for keratinocyte terminal differentiation, formation of the cornified envelope, and production of natural moisturizing factor (NMF). FLG deficiency leads to impaired epidermal barrier, increased transepidermal water loss, and enhanced allergen/microbial penetration, driving the inflammatory cascade." },
      { question: "A patient on dupilumab for severe AD develops bilateral eye redness and irritation at week 8 of therapy. What is the most likely cause?", options: ["Allergic conjunctivitis from environmental allergens", "Dupilumab-associated conjunctivitis", "Bacterial conjunctivitis requiring antibiotics", "Eczema herpeticum involving the eyes"], correct: 1, rationale: "Dupilumab-associated conjunctivitis occurs in 10-20% of patients and is a class-specific adverse effect unique to IL-4Ra blockade. The mechanism may involve disruption of conjunctival goblet cell mucin production by IL-13 inhibition. Management includes artificial tears, and ophthalmology referral if persistent. It does not typically require discontinuation of dupilumab." }
